tor` in tests is discouraged, but I might have to employ `ServiceLoader`. Instead, I could use `ClassLoader.loadClass` and `getConstructor().newInstance()`, although this still involves reflection. Using `URLClassLoader` is another option to consider.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing ClassLoader Behavior**\\n\\nI need to hide `TearDownTarget` and use the child loader for `loadClass` when the name matches `TearDownTarget`. It should throw `ClassNotFoundException`. For everything else, the parent loader should delegate. The `Class.forName(suiteName)` in the superclass uses the app loader, which can load `TearDownTarget`. If the target is hidden from the child, I wonder if setting the context loader to the child would work, since it would also fail. I'll add a package-private class `ShadowedTearDownOnVmCrash` in the same file, careful about resource paths in a native image.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Native Image Issues**\\n\\nI need to think about how the native image might fail early if a resource is missing, returning null instead of an `UnsupportedFeature`. I wonder if I can manage that null case effectively. It seems loading class bytes as resources might not be available in the native context, yet the test still shouldn’t be skipped just because of this potential issue. I’ll have to find a solution that handles null resources gracefully while ensuring that testing continues.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_6Ww4N5Oh7fBzk4rrasjhn8RT|fc_0d4ed4404535eaca016a26396b318081949d9a79190c75debd", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/tck-test-support/src/main/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/NativeImageSupport.java"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 860, "output": 986, "cacheRead": 28672, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30518, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 178088994